An astronomical phenomenon, better known as transit will appear as a small black dot crossing the sun’s face. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - If you look up into the sky this afternoon, you might just see how Mercury crosses the face of the sun. Occurrences like this are quite rare, and if you miss today's event, your next opportunity will be in 2032. Mercury's transit will be visible across Africa, weather permitting. READ: The sun blinding the path to Fourth Industrial Revolution So if you have a small telescope, get it out. But remember to not look directly into the sun as doing so can cause blindness. Rather project the image of the sun through the telescope onto a clean sheet of paper.